Rafael Correa in Quito this Monday.
To base the republic on socialism in the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
On Sunday, following the example of colleagues and friends, it was the latter who gave voice to the draft of a new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since, according to official results, 64% of voters voted "yes" to the referendum, on a basis of votes equal to 80%.
According to these results, the "no" was 28%, while 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% white papers.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it should get half the votes, plus one.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the exit of the polling stations and an estimate of a non-governmental organization had announced an overwhelming victory of the "yes", placing it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had claimed in the night between Sunday and Monday the victory of his draft Constitution.
The "Constitution triumphed gloriously," he had assured, congratulating Ecuadorians within the Guayaquil Governorate, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As always, Chávez and Morales congratulated Rafael Correa, as did his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The election, which took place quietly according to the election observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), was based on a text of 444 points aimed at consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the president.
This draft Constitution consecrates the power of the state over the economy, reserved to it the "development planning" of a country that lives essentially on the oil extraction implemented by large foreign companies and consequently on their currency.
Conceived by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also gives more power to the head of state, who can be elected for two consecutive four-year terms, and will have the opportunity to dissolve the assembly.
Correa has already announced his intention to take advantage of this amendment and to propose his candidacy for a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution also states that health and education services are free of charge, which the president has begun to promote in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It also bans the presence of foreign troops, a provision that will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for US anti-drug operations.
