The fox in the chicken coop
In America, life and health insurers, based on people’s drug purchase data, often refuse to sign an insurance contract.
Privacy experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
“There is a privacy program whereby the use of prescription drug data in any case depends on the approval of the person concerned.
This program must be in independent hands, otherwise it’s like entrusting the chicken to the fox,” writes the Washington Post citing Richard Dick, the program’s author to follow the prescriptions of the drugs.
Insurance companies subordinate the insurance rate and the amount due in case of damages to the health of the potential customer and, if they consider the risk too high, do not take out insurance.
A long time ago, the client had to undergo a medical visit and the contract was concluded only after the examination was completed.
Dick 10 years ago invented a much cheaper procedure: based on the customer's identification code, you can easily get information from pharmacies about what medicines he has purchased in the last year and a half and this program reveals what diseases he suffers from and in what health condition he is in.
For example, if you regularly buy large amounts of cholesterol reducers, this means that the level of fat in the blood is practically incurably high and is classified in the highest risk category.
There are several versions of the program on the market, some also determine the risk multiplier, to the insurer so in addition to paperwork, there is not much left, even if there are small difficulties.
Among the downsides is that some medicines are usable for multiple purposes, e.g. some compounds are usable against migraine or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter, from the insurance-commercial point of view, is a risk-increasing factor, the first two are not.
For the request and processing of data separate companies have been formed and these, before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies, ask for the approval of the patient.
Now the authorities are forcing her to do so even though they have not imposed fines for negligence so far.
Some companies have also recently processed the results of lab tests and linked them to medicine consumption data to provide a more accurate picture of patients’ health status.
More and more companies have access to data and, at the same time, controlling usage will be increasingly difficult.
There is a separate privacy law but its validity extends only to health services and insurance.
In front of Congress there is a bill that gives the authorities control competence to companies specializing in data service.
Richard Dick admits that it is not enough: for this reason he has developed a program that links the data transfer with the approval expressed by the person concerned.
Another issue is that the person concerned cannot so much deny approval because otherwise the insurers do not enter into the contract.
So then in the end the chickens are entrusted to the clemency of the fox.
